column1: 118000;instagram;2018-12-10 21:35:50;FALSE;"for years after i was molested and raped
when my parents found out about the molestation
column2: i was asked what i did to encourage it. i was 10 years old when it started. it's no wonder that i never told anyone when i was raped when i was 13.  my mind's process buried the memory in the back of my fear cabinet and didn't reference it for nearly 30 years.

column1: every time i watched a news story describing an assault on a child
column2: i was instantly outraged. i wanted every child predator punished and harshly. i would say things like 'he should be shot and pissed on' or 'they should put him in jail and throw away the key'

column1: the file in my fear cabinet gained intensity every time it was referenced and my negative perspectives about the men who hurt children was projected onto every man i encountered - both intentionally and unintentionally.
i took on a warrior attitude thinking i was helping myself stay safe and protected
column2: but i didn't understand how the law of attraction actually worked. my warrior attitude invited the very type of disrespectful men into my life - exactly who i wanted to avoid. this ensured my already rigid perspectives would be validated and reinforced.

column1: the only way to stop this cycle was to learn how to rewrite the files in the filing cabinets of my mind and forgive the men who harmed me.

it took me decades to heal. don't let that be your story. choose you over your anger. choose you over holding on to the resentments.  choose you over waiting for an apology that you won't get and choose you over the desire for revenge.

column1: writing a memoir deepened my compassion for others. sure
column3: i had been taught compassion by my parents. but writing memoir introduced me to a whole new authenticity of compassion. writing memoir involves deep introspection and interrogation
column4: and like any practice that exercises those muscles
column5: it makes you look at an experience from all points of view
column6: including the views and backstories of the characters who once hurt you. be it through abandonment. negligence. betrayal. physical
column8: or emotional violence. i expected to feel anger while revisiting those chapters and characters of my life. and i did feel anger. but the most prominent and lasting emotion was empathy. compassion. and sympathy.

column1: all of us were born as children. innocent and full of trust in the world. then
column2: it is through nonchalant or deliberate wounds that our faith is fractured. we become the love or the pain that is taught to us. in this there lives an invitation and potential for empathy
column4: forgiveness toward life and those who wound. in this there exists proof that every human is but a sum of choices
column8: we all hold the power and possibility to heal
column11: and evolve. we can choose love.

column1:
;216 personas asistieron al “ foro escúchame también ” , por los 16 días de activismo contra la violencia de género , que fue organizado por la defensoría del pueblo la agencia de las naciones unidas para los refugiados ( acnur ) venezuela en la sede de uneae en caracas . la inauguración del evento estuvo cargo de angélica izquierdo , directora de asuntos jurídicos de la defensoría del pueblo , dorialbys de la rosa , jefa de la unidad de terreno de acnur en distrito capital , quienes alentaron todos los presentes en el auditorio amplificar las voces de las víctimas de violencia sexual de género respaldar los esfuerzos iniciados para involucrar cada individuo , comunidad , sector organización , en la sensibilización formación de las redes de apoyo para sobrevivientes . en este sentido destacó de la rosa que el acnur “ está convencido de que el empoderamiento de las mujeres niñas , así como la igualdad de género opounidades , son medidas clave para prevenir el desplazamiento forzado promover el desarrollo humano sostenible ” . “ además trabajamos intensamente con el fin de asegurar que todas las personas que han tenido que huir de sus países por violencia sexual y/o por su identidad de género tengan acceso la protección jurídica social que les permita vivir libremente ” , precisó . la siguiente en tomar la palabra fue karolyn parra campos , directora de protección para la defensa de la mujer del ministerio público , quien subrayó durante su ponencia la impoancia del próximo aumento de la notidad de fiscalías nivel nacional , para atender los casos de violencia de género . `` esta es una excelente noticia , porque las sobrevivientes ahora podrán tener una mayor capacidad de respuesta '' . finalmente maría hernández royett , defensora nacional de los derechos de las mujeres , destacó la impoancia de establecer rutas de atención claras su difusión para el conocimiento de la comunidad general las sobrevivientes . ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ 📷 : ©acnur/ irma álvarez ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ del pueblo la agencia de la nacion unida para lo refugiado ( acnur ) venezuela en la sede de unea en caraca . la inauguración del evento estuvo cargo de angélica izquierdo , directora de asunto jurídico de la defensoría del pueblo , dorialbi de la rosa , jefa de la unidad de terreno de acnur en distrito capit , quien alentaron todo lo present en el auditorio amplificar la voce de la víctima de violencia sexual de género respaldar lo esfuerzo iniciado para involucrar cada individuo , comunidad , sector organización , en la sensibilización formación de la rede de apoyo para sobrevivient . en est sentido destacó de la rosa que el acnur “ está convencido de que el empoderamiento de la mujer niña , así como la igualdad de género opounidad , son medida clave para prevenir el desplazamiento forzado promov el desarrollo humano sosten ” . “ ademá trabajamo intensament con el fin de asegurar que toda la persona que han tenido que huir de su país por violencia sexual y/o por su identidad de género tengan acceso la protección jurídica social que le permita vivir librement ” , precisó . la siguient en tomar la palabra fue karolyn parra campo , directora de protección para la defensa de la mujer del ministerio público , quien subrayó durant su ponencia la impoancia del próximo aumento de la notidad de fiscalía nivel nacion , para atend lo caso de violencia de género . `` esta es una excelent noticia , porqu la sobrevivient ahora podrán tener una mayor capacidad de respuesta `` . finalment maría hernández royett , defensora nacion de lo derecho de la mujer , destacó la impoancia column1: 118067;instagram;2018-12-10 20:09:39;FALSE;70 years ago we adopted the universal declaration of human rights yet we still face huge human rights challenges worldwide and in the uk. sexual violence is a violation of a persons human rights. even the justice system in the uk which seeks to protect those rights openly violates other rights of survivors. at present the criminal justice system protects the perpetrator whilst the victim is violated over and over again by the invasive procedures of the cps. the violation of privacy and collection of data from victims is unlawful. the justice system is failing survivors and leaving them without justice or support. the current procedures used by the cps breach data protection and violate human rights law. we have got to fight for a fully just victim centred justice system. ‘injustice anywhere is a threat to justice everywhere’ #martinlutherking #humanrights #bigbrotherwatch #sistersuncut #thegeminiproject #endthesilence #believesurvivors #westandwithsurvivors #stopdefendingcriminals #supportsurvivors #endviolenceagainstwomen #justicenow #timeforchange #metoomvt #hearmetoo #timesup #metoo #justicewillprevail #standup4humanrights #humanrightsday #udhr70 #fuckthecps #survivorsnotsuspects #supportnotsuspicion #sistersunited #wedemandjustice #endsexualviolence;;en;#martinlutherking

;la agencia de las naciones unidas para los refugiados ( acnur ) en venezuela , en coordinación con la organización aliadas en cadena , presentó una muestra fotográfica en la población río negro , machiques de perijá ( estado zulia ) en el marco de los 16 días de activismo contra la violencia de género . la exposición contenía imágenes de las diferentes etapas del proceso formativo de la red mujeres de valor , integrada por indígenas de la etnia wayúu población local . durante la actividad , las mujeres compaieron sus experiencias el impacto que han tenido estas capacitaciones en sus vidas . también se elaboraron caeles con un llamado la `` violencia '' . ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ acnur aliadas en cadena trabajan conjuntamente en esta localidad para crear una red de mujeres , con el fin de generar 118091;instagram;2018-12-10 20:27:23;FALSE;"today marks 70 years since the universal declaration of human rights. this is eleanor roosevelt who as chair of the united nations human rights commission was the driving force in creating the 1948 charter of liberties which will always be her legacy: the universal declaration of human rights. this day we celebrate her legacy that now protects the rights of men and women across the world.
the human rights movement has made great strides over the past 7 decades but abuses still occur with saddening regulatory.
we should celebrate how far we’ve come but we also need to recommit to the principles outlined in the declarations 30 articles.

today also marks the final day of the 16 days of activism against gender based violence. it’s important we remember that women’s rights are human rights and we all must contribute towards a future where violence and harassment against women is not tolerated. 🙅🏻‍♀️

column1: at last year's embody goddess retreat the focus was on sexual healing (of course the #metoo movement was just erupting) but also the mount agung volcano began erupting as we began! she was transforming the rage of the feminine for and with us! •
she was activating and expressing the sheer power and passion as we reclaimed our own! 🔥🔥🔥 this year we are focusing on leadership. and specifically embodied feminine leadership.
because our world needs us to recognize that we are that and truly embody the qualities of being a leader - actually walking the talk. not talking the walk 😋
because as leaders we need nourishment too. gone is the paradigm of sheer force and burning out. we must fill up our own cups. no ifs or buts about it.

column2: because we need to do this new paradigm of leadership together.

118100;instagram;2018-12-10 20:33:23;FALSE;after i had my first child
column3: i thought i was the only mum who was struggling to adapt to motherhood
column4: the only mum who’s baby hardly slept and the only mum who struggled with feeding this new little human who depended on me completely. everyone else’s baby seemed to sleep all night and fed perfectly……what was i doing wrong?

column1: there was one completely life changing moment for me whilst getting a cuppa at a baby group i went to. one of the other mums just said “me too”…that was it …2 words. but that changed everything for me. i wasn’t the only one after all.
sometimes we feel like we are the only people in the world with the struggles we face. we think everyone else has it all together and we’re the only one that is struggling with motherhood
column3: body image or with deciphering all the conflicting nutritional information a google search can show up.

column1: having people who are going though the same struggles
column2: battles and journey as you means you feel supported
column3: understood and it certainly doesn’t feel like you’re the only one. it makes you feel like you can overcome anything because you have people who understand you.

column2: adapting and motivating themselves and each other together. it makes it so much easier than going it alone.

column1: 118115;instagram;2018-12-10 19:29:23;FALSE;"how will you serve this week?  there are so many ways to serve and every day it seems there are opportunities that pop up where we can step in and help. i know sometimes we may not be in a position where we can help monetarily
column2: but there are so many other ways that we can serve that doesn’t cost anything.

column1: encouragement is a simple gift we can give. pick a friend or family member each week and send an email
column2: text or handwritten note telling that person something positive...like maybe you noticed something that they did that week that you’re proud of or if they’re struggling send words of encouragement to lift them up.

column1: you can also offer your time to just listen. if there’s someone you’re proud of
serve to help someone shine!  xo

column1: 118153;instagram;2018-12-10 18:48:49;FALSE;"i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.
steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?
abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me
column2: a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

column1: the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagate™ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the fake content - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking a real responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.
and here comes the best part. trumq is truly playing along with his tweets

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

column1: 118174;instagram;2018-12-10 19:00:02;FALSE;"i’ve been seeing a lot of posts regarding the *controversy* over this song. i’ve seen posts suggesting that if you listen to rap music
column2: you shouldn’t be so offended by this song. i’ve seen feminist friends defend it. i’ve seen arguments break out and traditions being held on with a firm grip
column3: unwilling to let go. and i can’t help but wonder why. are we unwilling to look at things from the past and examine them
column4: with new perspectives? are we no longer willing to apply critical thinking to understand context and relevance? are we able to learn from the past and do better?

column1: i loved this song. i loved when zoe deschanel sang it in ‘elf.’ i loved seeing duets of this song. but i hadn’t really thought about it
column2: until recently. when i looked up the lyrics
column3: it is undeniably rapey. how many times does a woman need to say no?  why does this guy keep trying to coerce her
column5: and essentially try to trap her into staying? or is she just being coy and afraid of slut shaming?

column1: rap songs aren’t played at target or at children’s holiday concerts. i can’t imagine having been date raped and hearing this song repeat as i’m holiday shopping. can we all just pause for a moment to consider another perspective
column2: with some empathy? would it be so awful if we retired this song
column3: or requested that you enjoy it privately rather than have it blasting everywhere for the entire month of december? ❄️

column1: what are we holding onto by standing firmly in support of this song? and what are we willing to let go of in order to grow and progress as a society? is this really a message we want to instill in young boys and girls? ❄️ deep thoughts for this monday. i think we have an abundance of lessons to learn from these kinds of controversies. i’m not looking to argue
column2: but to invite and allow a new perspective. let’s release our attachments and choose to look through a new lens. maybe we’ll see things more clearly. know better

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?
abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the fake content - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking a real responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.
and here comes the best part. trumq is truly playing along with his tweets

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

column1: 118198;instagram;2018-12-10 18:14:19;TRUE;;"thank you @therumanproject for this lovely recognition ❤️ #repost @therumanproject with @get_repost

today is #internationalhumanrightsday and the last day of the un #16days of activism against gender based violence campaign. international human rights day marks the adoption of the international declaration of human rights on the 10th december 1948 by the un general assembly. it’s been celebrated every year since 1950.
to mark the end of the campaign
column2: we’re highlighting the activism of leyla hussain. leyla is a somali
column3: uk based campaigner and co-founder of daughters of eve. the organisation works to support women and girls who have experienced and are at risk of female genital mutilation. often profiled as a ‘muslim’ issue
column4: leyla has worked to combat damaging and narrow stereotypes that frame religion as key factor in its perpetration.

column1: speaking of the perceived role of culture and religion in relation to the issue
column4: as a somali woman i’m supposed to be at home being submissive and not speaking out
column5: and i think what people really struggle with is me saying: ‘i’m a proud muslim woman but i will speak about women’s issues and oppression and sex and relationships.' ""i’ve even had atheist feminists say ‘you cannot be a muslim if you’re going to talk about these things’ and i reply: ‘yes
column6: i am.’ because if you look at the teachings of islam
column7: they are about celebrating sexuality. yet no one actually reads those bits and that annoys me. in the quran it says you are not allowed to change how god made you
column8: so removing my genitals is totally un-islamic...when any form of violence or oppression becomes an issue in a community
column9: you will find religion is used as a means for excusing behaviours. and that’s by no means limited to the muslim community. when oppression is involved

column1: 118200;instagram;2018-12-10 18:15:05;FALSE;"to overcome is to overpower... to defeat... to prevail.
i #metoo'd a family member at the age of 14
column2: after years of abuse... & i overcame.

column1: i lost a loved one to suicide causing mass hysteria within my mind... & i overcame.
i found myself in a toxic relationship resulting in an eating disorder and attempted suicide... & i overcame.
i almost became homeless... & i overcame.
all of these things i used to use as reasons for why i could never see the other side of who i could be - the other side of what life could look like.
i used to feel shame for my weakness and that alone kept me from my greatest strength - overcoming.

column1: 118207;instagram;2018-12-10 18:19:11;FALSE;"today marks the final day in 2018’s #16daysofactivism against gender based violence as well as the #internationaldayofhumanrights •
this year we wanted to shed light on a very important issue & the theme of this year’s #16days - how to deal with domestic abuse in the workplace.
70% of those who experienced domestic violence were targeted at work. the majority of people who experience domestic violence are employed.
this is why standtall works with employers to help them address domestic abuse and support their staff in getting the help they might need. •

column2: speak up. ask your manager what your policy is for domestic abuse. find out how you can help. small actions can lead to big changes. •
together we can help end domestic abuse. •

column1: if you want to find out more about what you can do at your workplace email - contact@standtall.org
[image: illustration @hb_ink / the figures in grey are used to highlight those who suffer from domestic abuse in silence]

column1: 118218;instagram;2018-12-10 18:21:34;FALSE;"today marks the final day in 2018’s #16daysofactivism against gender based violence as well as the #internationaldayofhumanrights •
this year we wanted to shed light on a very important issue & the theme of this year’s #16days - how to deal with domestic abuse in the workplace.
70% of those who experienced domestic violence were targeted at work. the majority of people who experience domestic violence are employed.
this is why standtall works with employers to help them address domestic abuse and support their staff in getting the help they might need. •

column2: speak up. ask your manager what your policy is for domestic abuse. find out how you can help. small actions can lead to big changes. •
together we can help end domestic abuse. •

column1: if you want to find out more about what you can do at your workplace email - contact@standtall.org

column1: 70 years ago the universal declaration of human rights was adopted and proclaimed at the united nations general assembly in paris on 10 december 1948.
a milestone document that established for the first time the equal dignity and worth of every person and the inalienable rights everyone is entitled to as a human being.
today these principles continue to be the beacon of our society and the basis of our daily actions. let’s ensure humanity’s values are always upheld and never abandoned.
because if they are at risk
column2: we are all at risk too.

column1: 118254;instagram;2018-12-10 17:52:58;FALSE;"i've read so many opinions about the murder of grace millane. the 21 year old british backpacker killed in nz the night before her 22nd birthday. she was last seen in a hotel near a bar i've frequented for years and her body was found near where so many of my friends live and where so many of us go in summer to the numerous beaches and look out spots. my nz family are devistated that she survived months in south america then died in nz. i'm a kiwi writing this in liverpool. in the last 14 months i've been to 18 countries
column2: some of which alone and have attended more than one multi day festival alone too. i've read articles saying it's not her fault
column3: i've read others saying it's not safe for woman to be out alone or travel alone. this is my opinion on the matter.

column1: after #metoo i kept seeing 'it's not all men' and seeing my male friends upset about being tarnished with the same brush.
but i can say with absolute certainty that all women. everyone of your girlfriends
column7: daughters - all of us have had to think twice about outfits
column9: which way to walk home from the bus stop or train station (even if that ally way cuts out 15 mins walking and it's raining and we need to pee)
column10: we've walked with our keys threaded through our fingers
column11: not had headphones on at night
column12: made our friends text us when we got home and us them. we've shrugged off catcalls
column14: not worn that mini skirt that makes us feel like a super model because tonight you just can't be bothered dealing with all the arse grabs and cat calls that come with it. we order drinks in bottles so we can keep our thumbs over the top
column15: we take our drinks into toilets so they aren't drugged... in fact we do these things so often we don't even think about it anymore

column1: it's not all men but the problems are still with men. what are you doing to make your woman safer? parents what are you teaching your boys about consent and bodily awareness?
rip grace. one day i hope we know a world where it is safe to be a woman and we don't need to worry about these things anymore.

column1: 118259;instagram;2018-12-10 09:13:23;FALSE;"=====the cheese is calling and i am obliged to respond =====
went to meat the cheese a few ( add some more to few) days back and ordered some cult favourites. sinfully saying
column2: the choices we made were not to be regretted at all. ( unlike the life choices that always require contemplation)

column1: cheesy chick on a stick ( price rs 614) -- chicken skewers (or id like to call them ""chicken tikkai"" ) served on fries was quit a plain sight to see
column2: but served with an ample amount of cheese basically took our breath away.

column1: jalapeno chicken fries (price rs 614)-- the description said it had chicken. but i couldn't find any chicken. im actually pissed off on chicken. but again
column2: cheese made up for the lost chicken.

column1: sing me a medley (price rs 845) -- too busy to sing a medley cause we being stuffing our mouth with this perfectly cooked equally soft bursting with flavours holy grail chicken. am i saying too much chicken ??
deep fried pride (price rs 880)-- although i owe my friends a certain amount of gaalian for making me eat deep fried chicken

column1: 118263;instagram;2018-12-10 17:00:07;FALSE;"today marks the end of #16daysactivism against gender based violence. so we'll be sharing stories of survivors of several forms of gender based violence.
the picture on the left is me 12 years ago! then a victim now a victor! .

i am one of the few fortunate to be alive. some  left in a body bag and while many still suffer domestic violence because it remains widespread and is often considered ""socially acceptable” in nigeria. .

column2: friends and even some religious bodies do not see domestic violence as such a big deal. they believe it’s the outcome of provocation and admonish victims never to annoy their abusers . but these abusers don’t hit their bosses or colleagues who provoke them at work . they exercise restraints! .

column1: domestic violence is not a result of provocation. i’m writing this in capital letters and i hope it sinks in! violence and abuse is a tool used to enforce control
column2: power and fear in a relationship or marriage and not a momentary expression of anger.

column1: so stop judging victims by saying they were battered because of an imagined
column2: perceived or rumored wrong or asking them annoying questions like “what did you do that made him beat you”. questions like these are unintelligent and insensitive.
its criminal. real men don't use violence! we must all join hands to eliminate violence against women and girls. our women must feel and know that they are not alone! .

column1: there is no excuse for violence against women.  and yes
column2: no excuse for violence against men either.

column1: i am a victim turned victor ready to help other victims. join in

column1: 118272;instagram;2018-12-10 17:03:08;FALSE;"today marks 70 years since the universal declaration of human rights. ~
many simple yet radical ideas such as “all human beings are born free and equal” are enshrined in this important document. ~
the human rights movement has made great strides over the past 7 decades but abuses still occur with saddening regulatory. ~
we should celebrate how far we’ve come but we also need to recommit to the principles outlined in the declarations 30 articles. ~

today also marks the final day of the 16 days of activism against gender based violence. it’s important we remember that women’s rights are human rights and we all must contribute towards a future where violence and harassment against women is not tolerated. 🙅🏻‍♀️

column1: 118279;instagram;2018-12-10 17:05:12;FALSE;"real talk: i literally had a panic attack/ocd spike right before i went to the gym before my workout the other night. sometimes it just be like that 🤷🏻‍♀️
i’ve had ocd my entire life. but someone who loves me reminded me that we only live once. and we have to choose to think about the things that matter
column2: and let the negative shit go because it just isn’t worth entertaining. what a pep talk!!!!!

column1: went in the gym and repped 225lb on my squat that same night!!! it felt so good to put all of that negative energy into the weight. and i walked away with a stronger body
column2: and a stronger mind. i can’t change the fact that i was born with ocd
column3: but i can choose to channel it in positive ways. so can you 😘

column1: 118294;instagram;2018-12-10 17:13:05;FALSE;"it’s pretty obvious how this person feels lol. looking back at the election of 2016
column2: i know there were a lot of people who had serious difficulty with the “locker room talk” video that was released where trump touts grabbing women’s pussies. i know women who voted for him and blew the comments off as no big deal. i still love my friends that voted for him. i’ll never understand their rationale but i’ll always consider them my friends. in a time of american division
column3: it’s time to let go of petty arguments and agree that positive change for us all would be great. the craziness of the last couple years is surreal. whatever your political affiliation
column4: joking about assault is never okay. words lead to actions and a a society that can flippantly joke about assault is passively condoning it. i’m not happy about the division we’ve all felt but i’m happy about the strength and passion from fellow americans i have witnessed. take care ya’ll. -vu💜❤️⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

column3: it’s time to let go of petty arguments and agree that positive change for us all would be great. the craziness of the last couple years is surreal. whatever your political affiliation
column4: joking about assault is never okay. words lead to actions and a a society that can flippantly joke about assault is passively condoning it. i’m not happy about the division we’ve all felt but i’m happy about the strength and passion from fellow americans i have witnessed. take care ya’ll. -vu💜❤️⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

column1: 118349;instagram;2018-12-10 15:52:14;FALSE;appreciation post (essay alert!) 🙏🏽 right where do i even start! i have always admired carrie
column2: and i genuinely think she should be hugely recognised for her work within hip hop theatre and story telling with her choreography - i have learned so much from her!!! i got to work with her on my first job out of college and my god was i put in a cast full of absolute og’s within the hip hop scene. i was one of the understudies / swings in ‘some like it hip hop’ - my fav job to date and i honestly felt so so so privileged to learn about character / intention / truth and being honest to who i was as a performer from the way she directed and taught us. she has honestly helped me understand why dance is so universal and open to anyone and i’m so grateful she got to teach on one of my courses. i genuinely believe in great teachers and those stamping their names into our industry with integrity and passion and i want to bring those teachers in who are super passionate about spreading their knowledge and experience too! @carrieanneing - you’re an absolute g for this!!!! thank you so so much ❤️💜 heels and ‘feels’ - this isn’t just about putting your heels on

column1: 118365;instagram;2018-12-10 16:01:15;FALSE;"have you tried over and over and over again to loose the same 10
column3: 50 pounds?  have you found weight loss success in the past and then hit a plateau that seems as big as mt. everest because no matter what you do
column4: old habits keep creeping back in?  have you entered the holiday season telling yourself several times that ""this year will be different"" and yet you've already given up or had a major setback?

column1: well my friends......welcome to the table.  with me.  yep
column3: but this time i know exactly why.  fear.  you see
column4: i've had a lot on my plate the last 6 months and i let a few old habits creep back in when things got scary.  i've accomplished a ton of wonderful things personally
column6: i let my focus slide on my nutrition and i let fear hold me back in workouts because my old self was reminding me of what happened last time.

column1: last time i was at my peak of health
column2: having lost over 135lbs and entering competitive competitions for fun
column3: was when i was diagnosed with #achalasia and my world turned upside down.

column1: the last 1.5 years has been hard
column2: but i have never given up.  i have sat at the same weight almost this whole time
column3: but training for a new work position got the best of me the last few trips away.  so
column4: it's back to the focus board and i'm practicing what i preach to my clients who have been so successful in loosing over 100lbs between them!

column1: we focus on 2lbs at a time.  we drink more water (at lest 1/2 your weight in oz/day). we drink water before meals.  we eat veggies as our first bite off our plate.  we track everything that goes into our mouths
column2: and we recognize that food is either fuel or poison.  you can make small changes every day to help loose those extra pounds.  the first step is really recognizing you're uncomfortable
column3: and knowing regret kinda sucks.  big.  focus on 2lbs at a time
column5: and you can begin where you are at today.  not tomorrow. today.  who's with me in building their 2lbs board this week?  post it and tag me in it so i can celebrate with you as you move along in your journey!";;en;#Achalasia;;;;;0;;tigerstripesearned;Bri | Female Empowerment Coach;;0;False;1;0;0;31;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/ce70207528820fd1b8012a89aa43d17b/5D14ABFD/t51.2885-15/e35/43695412_388045628406363_5095811569397007335_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"have you tried over and over and over again to loose the same 10

column1: *the name of this body of work is entitled ""me too in art history"". i have re-created three famous art pieces; “are you jealous?” by paul gauguin
column3: and “self-portrait” by chuck close.  they are all mixed-media art quilts using scraps of fabric
column5: and various sewing techniques.  they have a satirical side which illustrates the sexual misconducts of the three original artists.  the women in the paintings are not represented as the artists originally intended
column6: but i  approached them in a way to represent their point of view while being the victims of sexual assault.  the questions at hand:  should we be celebrating the artworks from people who have a history of sexual deviance at the hands of others?  do the work of other artists accused of questionable conduct need to be recontextualized?

column5: and various sewing techniques.  they have a satirical side which illustrates the sexual misconducts of the three original artists.  the women in the paintings are not represented as the artists originally intended
column6: but i  approached them in a way to represent their point of view while being the victims of sexual assault.  the questions at hand:  should we be celebrating the artworks from people who have a history of sexual deviance at the hands of others?  do the work of other artists accused of questionable conduct need to be recontextualized?

column1: 118533;instagram;2018-12-10 12:13:41;FALSE;"today i got the chance to hang out with a few grade 8 students at american international school of lesotho(aisl)  we celebrated #humanrightsday by talking about different articles in the universal declaration of human rights and how we can each make the world a better place by protecting these rights.
the pupils also had a few questions about how they can become activists for social justice in their communities. all in all it was a great session
column2: we even ran out of time and couldn't discuss everything.

column1: very grateful to mr. mark brookes who is director at aisl for the invite. even more happy to hear how aware those kids were about their human rights and responsibilities towards their communities and the rest of the world.
looking forward to the next session
column2: maybe we will talk bodily autonomy next.

column1: 118539;instagram;2018-12-10 12:21:21;FALSE;"📷경제적 여유가 없는 여성은 꽃뱀 or 경제적 여유가 있는 여성은 성매매여성. 여성은 언제나 이 두가지 선택지에서 검열되고 있다.
📷역시 핸드폰보다 카메라로 찍은 사진이 색감도 화질이 더 좋다. 평소 카메라를 잘 사용하지 않지만
column2: 이렇게 여행때 카메라에 담긴 사진을 보고 있자니 카메라를 사길 잘 했다는 생각이 든다.

column1: 📷카메라와 관련된 일화들이 생각난다. 바야흐로 올해 여름쯤이었다. 당시 나는 핸드폰이 없이 아이패드만 생활을 했고
column2: 모든 사진들을 아이패드로 찍었다. 아이패드로도 충분히 카카오톡을 사용할 수 있었고
column3: 지인들과는 연락을 주고 받을 수 있었기에 불편함을 그다지 못느꼈다. 오히려 주변 사람들은 핸드폰이 없던 내게 핸드폰을 사라며 권유했었다.

column1: 📷선거운동이 끝나고 백만원 정도가 내 통장으로 입금되었고
column2: 나는 핸드폰이 아닌 카메라를 사고 싶었다. 당시 아나운서를 준비하던 중이라 카메라의 필요성을 느꼈고
column3: 또 유튜브에도 관심이 많았기 때문이다. 주위에서는 내게 카메라말고 핸드폰을 사라고 권유했다. 나는 새 핸드폰은 필요가 없고 카메라가 필요하다고 했다.

column1: 📷불필요한 논쟁이었다. 단지 나는 내가 필요한 것을 사고자 했을 뿐이었다. 그런데 그 과정에서 갑자기 어떤 남성들은 내가 유난히 카메라를 사고 싶어하는 것 같다며
column2: [카메라를 사달라는 거냐며] 꽃뱀이냐고 물었다. 나는 남성들에게 금전을 제공 받은 적이 단 한번도 없었고
column3: 그런것들을 받고자 하는 전혀 의도도 없었기에 그저 아니라고 대답했을뿐 [꽃뱀논란]에 대해 해명할 가치도 없다고 생각했었다.

column1: 📷지금 생각하니 너무 분하고 화가난다. 예쁜여자들은 얼굴만 믿고 남자에게 선물이나 돈을 원한다며 너도 그런 거 아니냐며 나를 추궁하던 무례한 질문들. 꽃뱀이냐는 질문에 돈이 부족하지 않다고 답하니
column2: 성매매를 하는건 아니냐며 되묻는 질문들. 이 질문 속에는 많은 것들이 담겨있다. 나에 대한 외모평가
column3: 예쁘다고 평가 받아지는 여성에 대한 편견. 그리고 여성을 성상품화하는 태도. 이런 모든 여성혐오를 겪으며 외모때문에 끊임없이 꽃뱀으로 의심받아온 나의 과거가 떠오른다.

column2: 나에게 연애의 대상으로 다가오는 남성들이 줄었다는 사실은 참 다행이다. 남성들은 아직도 내게 탈코르셋을 해서 인기가 없어지는 게 걱정되지 않냐며 묻지만
column3: 나는 남성에게 단지 [여성] 혹은 [연애대상]으로 비춰지지 않는 지금이 더 좋다.

column1: 📷연애는 상대가 일방적으로 나를 선택하는 게 아니다. 나에게도 내 취향과 감정에 따라 상대를 선택 할 수 있는 권리가 있다. 그리고 부디 나에게 금전을 댓가 삼아 내 감정을 얻고자 하는 남성들이 없었으면 한다. 내 감정은 물질적 가치와 교환 되어지는 것이 아니다.";;en;;;;;;0;;bibieungu;박은수 EunSoo Park 朴恩秀;;0;False;7;0;0;89;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/ca014d328ff3f937080cf63b455016a4/5D184AE6/t51.2885-15/e35/47251285_1939891476127978_8210363301450045750_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"📷경제적 여유가 없는 여성은 꽃뱀 or 경제적 여유가 있는 여성은 성매매여성. 여성은 언제나 이 두가지 선택지에서 검열되고 있다.

column1: 📷선거운동이 끝나고 백만원 정도가 내 통장으로 입금되었고

column3: 또 유튜브에도 관심이 많았기 때문이다. 주위에서는 내게 카메라말고 핸드폰을 사라고 권유했다. 나는 새 핸드폰은 필요가 없고 카메라가 필요하다고 했다.

column1: 📷불필요한 논쟁이었다. 단지 나는 내가 필요한 것을 사고자 했을 뿐이었다. 그런데 그 과정에서 갑자기 어떤 남성들은 내가 유난히 카메라를 사고 싶어하는 것 같다며

column1: 📷지금 생각하니 너무 분하고 화가난다. 예쁜여자들은 얼굴만 믿고 남자에게 선물이나 돈을 원한다며 너도 그런 거 아니냐며 나를 추궁하던 무례한 질문들. 꽃뱀이냐는 질문에 돈이 부족하지 않다고 답하니

column1: 118548;instagram;2018-12-10 12:30:28;FALSE;"today is #internationalhumanrightsday and the last day of the un #16days of activism against gender based violence campaign. international human rights day marks the adoption of the international declaration of human rights on the 10th december 1948 by the un general assembly. it’s been celebrated every year since 1950.
to mark the end of the campaign
column2: we’re highlighting the activism of leyla hussain. leyla is a somali
column3: uk based campaigner and co-founder of daughters of eve. the organisation works to support women and girls who have experienced and are at risk of female genital mutilation. often profiled as a ‘muslim’ issue
column4: leyla has worked to combat damaging and narrow stereotypes that frame religion as key factor in its perpetration.

column1: speaking of the perceived role of culture and religion in relation to the issue
column4: as a somali woman i’m supposed to be at home being submissive and not speaking out
column5: and i think what people really struggle with is me saying: ‘i’m a proud muslim woman but i will speak about women’s issues and oppression and sex and relationships.' ""i’ve even had atheist feminists say ‘you cannot be a muslim if you’re going to talk about these things’ and i reply: ‘yes
column6: i am.’ because if you look at the teachings of islam
column7: they are about celebrating sexuality. yet no one actually reads those bits and that annoys me. in the quran it says you are not allowed to change how god made you
column8: so removing my genitals is totally un-islamic...when any form of violence or oppression becomes an issue in a community
column9: you will find religion is used as a means for excusing behaviours. and that’s by no means limited to the muslim community. when oppression is involved

i  been trying really hard to keep up a brave face lately + be positive +  adress serious topics but...these panphobics are really getting to me + its only making my seasonal depression worse. i try and tell myself to toughen up +  i should be used to bring bullied for being pan because i always have been but i don't wanna be used to it. i shouldn't have to be used to it.
i love myself for being pansexual and that's who i am.

during the abuse i pushed away my sexuality  so they would stop hurting me.. i went numb + venomous + i wanted to die with every fider of my soul.. but i found strength in who i was then  i got the courage to rebel and i loved myself and my sexuality ever since because it gave me strength when all my strength was ripped from me.
so it hurts a lot to hear such horrid things. it hurts on a level they'll never be able to understand. i'm trying to do my best i really am its just so hard right now. it hurts a lot. ~ witchy

column1: 118641;instagram;2018-12-10 08:25:20;FALSE;"it's about to get real here. this ones a little tough for me to write.
so about last night... i got triggered. i got triggered bad. i had my first date in spain. on paper
column2: super great guy: strong family values
column5: and very easy on the eyes 😉

column1: things were going well until he kissed me. this is usually the exciting part of a good date
column2: but for me it through me off. why? he didn't  give me an option to kiss him back. he threw himself at me mid sentence. i gave him a look 🧐 but that didn't stop him from trying again.
showered and just started to cry. i couldnt quite understand why. that's just not like me to get emotional over things i can't understand. i felt like shit!

column1: it wasn't until i was drifting off to sleep that it clicked.

for those of you who have been following me you'll know that this year i came out about my past traumas with sexual abuse. what happened made my body react even though my mind couldn't realize it. it is obviously still attempting to block my past out.
i could choose to continue to feel terrible about what had happened to me
column2: but instead i choose to feel empowered! i am happy to have quickly recognized the trigger and i do not allow my past to control my present.

column1: i get to take back my power today! today is amazing! i am happy
column2: heslthy and safe!  and i appreciate what happened last night
column3: because it brings me closer to meeting the man that i will feel safe and comfortable with.

column1: the universe doesnt conspire against us
column2: although it may seem that way. the universe tests us
column3: to see if we are truly ready for the next step in life; to live a more full and abundant life of all the things we truly desire.

column1: i pray that you will use these tests given to you to find your dream life 🤗💖💕

column1: 118675;instagram;2018-12-10 09:29:46;FALSE;"""one day i had to go to mirigama
column2: and i was a little confused as to which bus to take
column3: so i asked a nice looking old person. a few minutes into waiting
column4: he got on the same bus and sat next to me. i wasn't too alarmed yet
column5: and he even confirmed my bus-stop with the driver for me. after the bus started
column6: he began making small talk. he then fell asleep
column8: began to lean into me. eventually he was leaning on me the entire time. i woke him up for his stop
column9: but he kept sitting next to me. suddenly
column10: he wanted to exchange contact information
column11: and that's when i noticed the red flag. i kept saying no
column12: but he pushed even more. he then told me that he developed feelings for me
column13: and that he wanted to be even close to me. i kept saying no
column14: and i froze out of shock. he got more aggressive
column15: and said he missed his stop for me. he also said he knew where i lived
column16: and would follow me home. my stop finally came
column17: and i stood up to leave. but he kept blocking me
column18: so i jumped over him and tried to run for it. but he grabbed my ankle. i shook him off and ran for my life onto another bus. once i got home
column19: i told my family about my encounter. they told me it was normal
column20: and that i shouldn't travel alone. i decided to never use public transport ever again after that"" - opula

column1: 118718;instagram;2018-12-10 05:53:59;FALSE;"this is the face of a women trying so damn hard to keep it together. so i’m going to tell a little pinch of my past to do with systematically falling into one domestic violent relationship to the next. when i was 11 years old i spent a lot of time at one of my bestfriends houses & we were just happy innocent kids looking for ways to entertain ourselves in a small country town with the population of around 500 people.. or even less back then. anyways her older brother started to show an attraction too me but not in any type of healthy ways
i won’t go into details as i myself don’t want to have to relive it again. but he raped me
column2: and that was the end of my friendship with his sister and basically i had no idea what the hell had even happened too me until 3 years later on when i was sexually attacked by an unknown man walking home from the shops late one afternoon. i was taken to hospital & treated for trauma etc. strange thing is that now at 26yrs old i only really remember laying in a hospital bed with my dad complaining about having to pay the ambulance bill
column3: my brain has kind of blocked out the rest somehow. only gods knows for what reason after these events
column4: i started to only have an attraction for older men someone who i believed would protect me and help me be safe at all times
column5: little did i know i was setting myself up for the worst ride of my life. i felt depersonalised i didn’t know myself and started to rely on who ever i was seeying at the time to create my happiness. which was always shattered since i never had a steady
column6: official relationship with anyone until i turned 18.  then i thought i found the love of my life... the one man every single person i know told me too stay away from
column7: even i had sirens going off in my head but chose to ignore them
column11: everything i could of hoped for
column12: it was so intense and i fell so damn hard
column13: but only 2 weeks into our relationship he started playing mind games with me
column14: accusing me of sleeping with his mates which of coarse i didn’t i was too blinded by love to even see another males existence. tbc

column1: 118787;instagram;2018-12-10 05:31:44;FALSE;people have expectations of who you should be... how you should be... i’m just here being me. healing my trauma the best way i know how. playing catch up. trying to learn all the things i wasn’t given the opportunity to. being that my main focus coming up was survival. and attempting to keep up with everything thrown my way on a daily... trying to adhere to every expectation. what it means to be black.. to have lighter skin.. to be woke.. to be a healer.. to be a girl from the hood who can be very ratchet at times. sometimes who i am changes from moment to moment. and that can be shocking to people with preconceived notions.. expectations.. projections. but i don’t care. i won’t be chained to any identity... i can only be.. right here.. in this moment.. just out here being... 💯 i’m not the most eloquent speaker
column2: but still speaking my truth nonetheless.. tending my wounds the best way i know how. doing better every time i know better... sometimes i get overwhelmed. a lot of times. easily overwhelmed. my little sensitive self. it knocks me down
column3: but i get back up. dust off. keep going. everyday is a new day. a new me. a better version is the goal... healing myself to heal my momma and all the mommas before her.. to plant healthy seeds. to be the change i wish to see.. i change my mind to change my world. i know i’m the only one i can change. and i know changing what i don’t like within the universe inside of me is the only way to change what i don’t like in the world around me. as within so without. even if that simply means i begin to only attract that which matches my vibrations... anyways if you’re still reading  i’m working on a new personal project. i’ve actually been working on it for a while. sometimes progress moves at a snail’s pace. inching along. i become overwhelmed and just walk away from it for a while. but even if i’m only taking baby steps each day
column4: it’s still movement. and movement is good. follow along with me in the meantime in between time. if you want. 👉🏾 @mymomwasoncrackbutimstilldope .. i appreciate the support. ❤️;;en;;@mymomwasoncrackbutimstilldope;;;;0;;frankienicole_;Frankie Nicole;;0;False;16;0;0;79;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/c0850b5eadf1e38f5ae5eb953edb81c7/5D1E267B/t51.2885-15/e35/46649066_1981276561967358_4621833497747259782_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;people have expectations of who you should be... how you should be... i’m just here being me. healing my trauma the best way i know how. playing catch up. trying to learn all the things i wasn’t given the opportunity to. being that my main focus coming up was survival. and attempting to keep up with everything thrown my way on a daily... trying to adhere to every expectation. what it means to be black.. to have lighter skin.. to be woke.. to be a healer.. to be a girl from the hood who can be very ratchet at times. sometimes who i am changes from moment to moment. and that can be shocking to people with preconceived notions.. expectations.. projections. but i don’t care. i won’t be chained to any identity... i can only be.. right here.. in this moment.. just out here being... 💯 i’m not the most eloquent speaker

column2: ” the newest play by the celebrated british playwright mark ravenhill
column3: is one of the strongest contemporary critiques of male power and privilege that i’ve seen staged.  a popular male teacher is about to retire after forty-five years of service. but there’s a catch—he’s being held accountable for past egregious actions by an angry growing mob of former students outside his house
column4: and by his estranged adult daughter who arrives with her own motives to shake things up. the man begins to recognize that he represents a generation of white male power whose tyranny is so naturalized that it remains unremarkable—until now. i won’t give away the ending or include any other spoilers
column5: but i will say this: the writing is surprisingly restrained.  ravenhill and vicky featherstone
column7: reign in the hysteria while still keeping the stakes high and the tension real. there’s a lot of talking
column8: and the actors (all award-winning veterans of the london stage) expertly do their part to build the play’s mounting tension. ravenhill’s earlier work such as “shopping and fucking” and “mother claps molly house” brought him international fame. and while he’s out as queer and living with hiv
column9: this world premiere foregrounds an entirely new political landscape. “the cane” retains the radical critique of social norms typical of his work and yet it does more. it moves the critique into our immediate moment and takes on the foundation of patriarchy
column10: which is habitual abuse rendered as the way of the world. it’s an intense—even creepy—play
column11: and i hope it generates lots of attention here in london. it’s a great production
column13: and it provokes audiences to consider the consequences of patriarchal power and control.  these are the issues we need to engage these days and this is the kind of theatre our times demand.

column1: 118909;instagram;2018-12-08 05:25:43;FALSE;"olivia turano | junior | ford school of public policy
olivia shares that a lot of her feelings of safety are related to her sexuality and with the current political climate
column2: she has felt more unsafe. “when i was in high school
column3: i never really thought about being bi … as something where i would face severe problems or discrimination in my life. i never really thought there would reasonably be policy that would attack my rights or my abilities
column4: but i think in the past few years i’ve had to think about that a little bit more. nothing has ever happened to me that’s bad or anything
column5: but it is so much more on my radar than it otherwise would be. and i think as a woman it’s a similar situation. where obviously
column6: it wasn’t like when obama was president it was a perfectly equal world
column7: at all. there were so many of the problems that are still here today
column8: but especially with this whole #metoo movement and with kavanaugh being nominated
column9: and with the concern over roe v. wade… like i think if you had asked me in high school “will roe v. wade be overturned?” i would have been like “absolutely not

column1: 1. do you believe in any movements?

column2: i completely believe in the motives and actions of national movements like black lives matter
column5: and local organizations within nyc that fight for affordable housing and against gentrification.

column1: 1a-b. are you a part of a movement? are you active in it?
i don’t think i would identify as belonging to a particular movement. however
column2: i do try to show up to protests and special events
column3: and i donate to these organizations whenever i can.

column2: yes. black and latino students in the nyc public school system are at a disadvantage from the very start
column3: since majority-minority public schools do not see that same kind of investments in largely white public schools. that kind of educational disadvantage leaves a lifelong impact
column4: where new yorkers of color may have fewer economic opportunities available to them. but as a black alumnus of a majority white private high school
column5: i was fortunate to not deal with those stacked odds. however
column6: i am hyper-conscious of my behavior around my classmates and teachers because i do not want to be associated with a stereotype or be a reflection of anti-black bias. so black boys and young black men like me still face individual struggles rooted in systemic biases
column7: whether it is dealing with microaggressions or institutions that limit opportunities of success

column1: 3. do you believe that your generation is making a difference?
i definitely believe that my generation is making a difference in fighting against oppressive forces in government
column3: and in everyday life. this generation is using networking tools like social media to organize and mobilize movements (with march for our lives and #metoo being the most recent examples). i hope people are also aware that social media can promote “slacktivism”
column4: which is low-effort involvement like signing a petition and is no substitute for taking direct action like going to protests and voting on election day.";;en;#MeToo;;;;;0;;voicevote;#VOTEVOICE;;0;False;0;0;0;18;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/e0e227985d5a53afdc9de0701b199bd9/5D1FBD0E/t51.2885-15/e35/47042029_2286897624866774_9076460532306274218_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"andrew brown:

column1: 118990;instagram;2018-12-09 22:54:37;FALSE;"some may say...”how do i raise a child in such a scary world?!"" (no i don’t thing everyone and everything is scary by any means). in my case
column2: i look at this small little baby girl and think literally she is my heart walking outside of my body - it truly makes me pretty terrified of just about anything. if anything were to happen to my little girl
column3: i don’t know what i would do - and as i write this i am writing knowing that many parents have had to live through something horrible happening to their tiny humans...i am truly in awe of their courage

column1: i have always wanted to change the world
column2: but i truly don't have the powers to do that alone...but instead of sitting in silence
column3: i will start by raising my child and hoping you too raise your children to start the change in this world
column4: because they are all capable of changing this world with our guidance. we won't sit on the sidelines
column5: or wait for the world to change itself. for me as a mother
column13: etc...we truly have the best role there is...we have the chance to raise those who will be the ones to stand up for those in need
column14: and who will stand up in the name of freedom
column17: and justice. we are the one raising our child...not the world...we have the chance to be the greatest of activists
column18: and with that our children will become the change we need in the world.
